title: More rain, flooding forecast along soggy East Coast
text:
By SETH BORENSTEIN and DAVID DISHNEAU
Associated Press Even with Hurricane Joaquin no longer as big of a threat, the weekend promises little relief for the most waterlogged parts of the East Coast.
The National Weather Service says flooding remains a concern through Monday morning, especially in parts of North and South Carolina that already have received up to 11 inches of rain this week. Forecasters say some areas could see storm totals as high as 15 inches.
Meteorologists say once the rain ends, the threat of flooding persists because the ground is too saturated to absorb water. And high winds could bring down trees like the one that hit a vehicle near Fayetteville, North Carolina, killing a passenger.
The storm also has been linked to a drowning in Spartanburg, South Carolina.
Flood watches and warnings also are in effect in Delaware and parts of New Jersey, Maryland and Virginia.
